1) Bad prompt
Build a Spring Boot CRUD app using JSONPlaceholder comments API.
Why this is bad

It does not tell the AI:

what architecture to use
whether this is external API integration or in-memory CRUD
which HTTP client to use
whether validation is needed
how errors should be handled
what exact endpoints to expose
what quality level is expected

2) Medium prompt
Create a Spring Boot application for JSONPlaceholder comments API.

Requirements:
- Expose CRUD endpoints for comments
- Use Java and Spring Boot
- Keep the code clean
- Use DTOs
- Add a service layer

3) Excellent prompt
Act as a senior Java Spring Boot developer.

Build a small but production-style Spring Boot application that wraps the external JSONPlaceholder comments API.

External API:
- Base URL: https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com
- Resource: /comments

Internal API requirements:
- Expose these endpoints:
  - GET /api/comments
  - GET /api/comments/{id}
  - POST /api/comments
  - PUT /api/comments/{id}
  - DELETE /api/comments/{id}

Technical requirements:
- Use Java 21 and Spring Boot 3.x
- Use layered architecture:
  - controller
  - service
  - client
  - dto
  - exception
- Use Spring RestClient for external API calls
- Use constructor injection only
- Read external base URL from application.yml
- Do not call external API directly from controller
- Do not use field injection
- Do not use Object.class
- Do not generate in-memory CRUD using ArrayList


Validation requirements:
- Validate create/update request using Jakarta Validation
- email must be validated properly
- required fields must be enforced

Error handling requirements:
- Add global exception handling using @RestControllerAdvice
- Handle downstream 4xx, 5xx, and connection errors cleanly
- Return structured error response

Output requirements:
1. Show package structure
2. Generate all classes
3. Generate application.yml
4. Keep code concise but realistic
5. Do not use pseudocode
